		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2008 SI"></a><br><code>sle2008s/paper04</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2008 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>Engineering of Framework-Specific Modeling Languages</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MichałAntkiewicz.html">Michał Antkiewicz</a>, <a href="../profile/KrzysztofCzarnecki.html">Krzysztof Czarnecki</a>, <a href="../profile/MatthewStephan.html">Matthew Stephan</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1109/TSE.2009.30">10.1109/TSE.2009.30</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The paper proposes a method and exemplars for engineering framework-specific modelling languages, a form of domain-specific language tailored to a framework.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3f.html"><span class="tagL">T3F: API</span></a><ul><li> The languages are explicitly centred on framework APIs, capturing API abstractions/rules and modelling application usage of APIs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It discusses language tooling/engineering workflows (including reverse/forward/round-trip engineering) needed to support FSML use cases.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
